description:
Our php connection code is essentially this:

$start_time = round(microtime(true)*1000);
$dbconnstr = 'ec2-east-db1,ec2-east-db2,ec2-east-db3';
$options = array('replicaSet' => 'replica1', 'timeout' => 500);
try{
    self::$connections[$dbconnstr] = new Mongo($dbconnstr, $options);
} catch (Exception $e) {
    $stop_time = round(microtime(true)*1000);
    log('exception', 'time took: ' . ($stop_time - $start_time));
}

But we just had a ec2-east-db36 become degraded for a period of time.. and this ended up causing a 230 second delay when trying to construct the new connection.  This is only one instance of the failure.. there were many.. and they significantly impacted our apache processes by piling up connections.

On the affected replica set, connections went from ~800 to over 4,000 as apache opened up more and more connections.  This also blew out the PHP connection pool for the driver and forced new connection creation across all replica sets.

Why would the mongo constructor not honor the timeout?  I understand this is an older driver, and we are in the process of upgrading to the newer 1.2.7+ versions.. but I'd like to see if you have any insights into whether this issue still exists?  (It'd be nice to know the commit that fixed it in case we need to roll our own version.)

If the value %20L is used in a string that you are inserting into the Mongo _id field - and that _id is a duplicate - then the Mongo PHP driver will crash with the following uncatchable error: "PHP Fatal error:  Illegal length modifier specified 'o' in s[np]printf call"

To replicate, just run the following code:

	$m = new MongoClient();

	try {
		$dbtest = $m->test;
		$dbtest->test->insert(array('_id'=>'hello%20London', 'added'=>time()));
	} catch (Exception $e) {
	}

	try {
		$dbtest = $m->test;
		$dbtest->test->insert(array('_id'=>'hello%20London', 'added'=>time()));
	} catch (Exception $e) {
	}

It should just output the normal catcheable error:

Uncaught exception 'MongoCursorException' with message 'localhost:27017: E11000 duplicate key error index: test.test.$_id_

